                                                              1. interface changes
                                                              =====================

--> Interface means collection of abstract methods.
Note: The method which doesnot contain any body is called as abstract method.

-> A class can implements interface using "implements".

-> When a class is implementing interface its mandatory that class should implement all abstract methods of that interface otherwise class can not be compile.
-> Here I am taking one interface with one abstract method. All the classes which are implementing that interface should override interface methods(s).


interface Vehicle{
public abstract void startVehicle();
}

class Car implements Vehicle{

public void startVehicle(){

//logic to start car
   }
}

class Bus implements Vehicle{
public void startVehicle(){

//logic to start bus
   }
  
}
class Bike implements car{

public void startVehicle(){

//logic to start bike
   }

}



=> if we add new method in interface then Car, Bike and Bus will fail at compile time.
=> To overcome above problem we will use Default and Static methods.

1. interface can have concreate method from 1.8v.....
2. Interface concreate method should be default or static.....
3. Default methods we can override in impl classes.....
4. interface static methods we can't override in impl classes........
5. We can write multiple default and static methods in interface.....
6. Default and Static method introduced to provide backward compatability.......

Ex: forEach() method added in java.util.Iterable interface as default method in 1.8v.......



Below is the example:
=====================

package DefaultInterfaceDemo;

/*
 * 
 *   This program is based on Default and Static methods in interface changes
 * 
 * 
 * 
 * 
 */


interface Vehicle {
	
	public void start();
	//this can be override 
	public default void clean(){
		System.out.println("my car is cleaning....");
	}
	
	//we will go for static method if we don't want any one do the modification to my method like override 
	public static void stop(){
		System.out.println("my car is cleaned....");
	}
}

public class Car  implements Vehicle{

	@Override
	public void start() {
			System.out.println("car start");
	}	
	
	@Override
	public void clean() {
		System.out.println("my clean method................");
	}
	
	public static void main(String[] args) {
		
		Car c = new Car();
		
		c.start();
		
		c.clean();
		
		//we will call static method in this way 
		Vehicle.stop();
	}

}




